<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1486,2035]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1625,1650]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognised by second antennal segment entirely yellow, corium with large triangular vague brownyellow pouch at base, cuneus red, with large black spot near external margin (
<figureCitation box="[1101,1206,1660,1685]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1245,1267]" captionTargetBox="[240,1347,618,1223]" captionTargetId="figure-539@30.[240,1347,618,1223]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 9. Cuneus and posterior margin of corium, dorsal view. A, Polymerus holosericeus; B, P. russatus sp. nov., holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5079600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5079600/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 9 B</figureCitation>
) and left paramere hypophysis with straight superior margin before apex from lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[977,1077,1694,1719]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1928,1950]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,201,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-84@22.[155,1432,193,1907]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left paramere of Polymerus, left view. A, P. nigrita; B, P. unciniger sp. nov.; C, P. holosericeus; D, P. russatus sp. nov.; E, P. pekinensis; F, paratype of Poeciloscytus funestus; G. P. amurensis. Scale bare: 0.14 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5079580" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5079580/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 3 D</figureCitation>
). This species is closely related with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hahn" authorityYear="1831" box="[208,377,1729,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Polymerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holosericeus">
<emphasis box="[208,222,1730,1753]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[236,377,1729,1754]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">holosericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and differs from it by following characters: longitudinal carina on right wall of posterior right lobe of vesica long, almost reaching lobe apex, latter not extended and not bent upwards, basal sclerite on rightinferior surface of posterior right lobe dilated and heavily sclerotised distally (
<figureCitation box="[1023,1133,1798,1823]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1856,1878]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,328,1784]" captionTargetId="figure-175@31.[151,1436,303,1808]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 10. Vesica of Polymerus. A–C, vesica of P. holosericeus; D, posterior right lobe of vesica of P. russatus sp. nov., holotype. Right (A, D), superior (B) and anterior (C) view. all—anterior left lobe; arb—anterior right bladder; bab –basoapical sclerotised band; bs—basal sclerite of posterior right lobe; ds—ductus seminis; lc—longitudinal carina of posterior right lobe; ms—medial spicule; pb—posterior bladder; pll—posterior left lobe; ppll—postposterior left lobe; prl—posterior right lobe; ps—posterior spicule; sgas—supragonoporal area of sclerotisation; sp—spinulose plate; sps—superio-posterior spicule. Scale bare: 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5079602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5079602/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 10 D</figureCitation>
), medial lobe of gynatrium with wide base and without any sclerotization on ventral wall, medial protrusion on dorsal margin of interramal sclerite triangular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="34" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[151,1436,1486,2035]" lastBlockId="33.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="33" lastPageNumber="34" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1902,1927]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[353,490,1902,1927]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Colouration</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[507,650,1902,1927]" captionStart="FIGURE 40" captionStartId="81.[151,250,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[169,1419,213,1865]" captionTargetId="figure-121@81.[162,1420,193,1885]" captionTargetPageId="81" captionText="FIGURE 40. Polymerus species, habitus. A, P. (Pachycentrum) carpathicus, male; B, P. (Pachycentrum) nigrita, female; C, P. (Pachycentrum) unciniger sp. nov., male; D, P. (s. str.) holosericeus, female; E, P. (s. str.) russatus sp. nov., male; F, P. (s. str.) russatus sp. nov., female; G, P. (s. str.) pekinensis; H, holotype of Poeciloscytus funestus, male; I, paratype of Poeciloscytus funestus, female; J, Polymerus (s. str.) amurensis, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5079701" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5079701/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 40 E, F</figureCitation>
). Head before antennae often with two brownish-yellow spots. In all studied females strip on posterior margin of pronotum wider than in male, entire xyphus of prothorax, apex of scutellum, narrow strip along external margin of corium, bases of femora, dorsal surface of abdomen in its base and large spot on each side of abdominal venter brownish-yellow. Xyphus of prothorax in male black, with yellow edging. Triangular spot at base of corium large in females, smaller in male. Apex of cuneus red in males and yellow in females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,151,464]" box="[199,1406,223,248]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis box="[199,371,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Right paramere</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[385,476,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1773,1795]" captionTargetBox="[170,1420,196,1748]" captionTargetId="figure-152@19.[162,1424,193,1752]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 2. Right and left parameres of Polymerus species. A–G, right paramere; H–J, left paramere. A, H–J, P. carpathicus; B, P. nigrita; C, P. unciniger sp. nov.; D, P. holosericeus; E, P. russatus sp. nov.; F, P. pekinensis; G, P. amurensis. Left (H), posterior (I) and right (J) view. Scale bare: 0.14 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5079576" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5079576/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 2 E</figureCitation>
), 
<emphasis box="[496,565,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">vesica</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[617,730,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">gynatrium</emphasis>
as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hahn" authorityYear="1831" box="[794,959,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Polymerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holosericeus">
<emphasis box="[794,807,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[821,959,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">holosericeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except characters listed in the diagnosis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,260,285]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin word 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gapon" authorityYear="2014" box="[524,616,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Polymerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="russatus">
<emphasis box="[524,616,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">russatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
means “stained with blood”, “covered with gore”, this specific name are given owing to dark red cuneus of this species.
</paragraph>
